data.content:
Here's your test rewritten with specific MSTest 3.x assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**What changed and why:**

| Original | Replacement | Better because |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "expected non-empty collection" instead of "expected True, got False" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure shows actual count vs expected |
| `.Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(filtered)` | Asserts exactly one match; returns the element if you need it |

The `users.All(u => u.IsActive)` line is fine as `Assert.IsTrue` — there's no built-in "all match predicate" assertion in MSTest, so `Assert.IsTrue` is the right choice there.
